## Basic Onboarding/Offboarding

| Function        | Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Onboarding      | The process of a new employee entering an organization, officially being hired and gaining access to certain privileges and/or materials.                                                                                                                       |
| Career Mobility | The employee moves to a new position, thereby gaining access to a new set of privileges and/or materials.                                                                                                                                                       |
| Offboarding     | The employee exits employment due to a contract expiration or, for example, immediate dismissal. All access to privileges and materials must be blocked and revoked at the appropriate time.                                                                    |
| External Management | Managing external workers, who are usually not permanent employees but still need access to privileges and materials. Due to their limited engagement, they should only be granted access when they are actively working.                           |

## Roles

| Function               | Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |
|------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Role Management        | Issuing and assigning rights within the role model. A role manager is responsible for granting and issuing rights according to (legal) standards to the appropriate person.                                                                                                            |
| Group Management       | Issuing and assigning rights to certain composite groups, it can be useful to set up a group of users as a group.                                                                                                                                                                   |
| RBAC                   | "Role Based Access Control" is an approach to restrict system access to authorized users. Access is granted to stakeholders and not to third parties.                                                                                                                             |
| ABAC                   | Within "Attribute-Based Access Control," access rights are associated with a set of rules expressed in measurable attributes (think of roles). Access rights are granted to users who can prove that they meet the attributes.                                                   |
| Identity Store         | The location where users and roles are managed, essentially a kind of database.                                                                                                                                                                                                      |
| Authentication         | Moving the correct identity information from the source system to the target system. Put simply: the verification that someone is indeed the person in question.                                                                                                                   |
| Deduplication          | Eliminating duplicate instances. Manual registration often leads to duplicate licenses or accounts of paid services, resulting in unnecessary costs. Deduplication removes these unnecessary instances, leading to significant savings by, for example, no longer paying double licenses for one employee. |
| Multiplicity Support   | Efficiently processing staff with multiple roles or tasks within a company. This way, duplicate registrations within the system are prevented, potentially resulting in duplicate issuance of paid licenses or other material.                                                        |
| REST API               | An application program that uses HTTP requests to obtain data. REST (Representational State Transfer) is a set of rules that developers follow when creating their API (Application Programming Interface).                                                                              |

## Security

| Function                     |Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   |
|------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| PAM-light                    | A system that grants the necessary rights to administrators, but with the necessary limitations to keep third parties like hackers out. After all, an administrator has the power to seriously damage business operations; for example, by only granting access at fixed times, an unauthorized person with the necessary information still cannot log into the administrative system.                                                                                                                                                         |
| Policy Management            | The process of creating, communicating, and maintaining policies and procedures within an organization. The aim is to ensure smoother internal processes.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  |
| Red Button Procedure         | A procedure within IAM that deals with an urgent case not covered by the system. This could include immediate dismissal or sudden death. The system needs to be updated to prevent incorrect registration; otherwise, it will use the end date of the contract.                                                                                                                                                                            |
| Green Button Procedure       | A procedure within IAM that deals with an urgent case not covered by the system, but in a more positive way. For example, an employee may have signed a contract that starts on a certain date, but if desired, they can of course start working before the privileges and access to materials actually begin.                                                                                                                                 |
